---
import ArticleLayout from "../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro";

const title = "BC PNP vs CRS Calculator: Which One Should You Use?";
const description = "Comprehensive comparison between the BC PNP Skills Immigration Ranking System and Canada Express Entry CRS. Find out which pathway gives you the best chance for PR.";
---

<ArticleLayout slug="bc-pnp-vs-crs-calculator" datePublished="2026-01-29" dateModified="2026-02-09" keywords="BC PNP vs CRS, BC PNP vs Express Entry, SIRS vs CRS comparison" title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 sm:py-20">
    
    <!-- Hero Header -->
    <header class="mb-16 text-center">
      <div class="inline-flex items-center justify-center w-20 h-20 bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-500 to-pink-600 rounded-3xl mb-8 shadow-xl shadow-purple-200">
        <svg class="w-10 h-10 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
          <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19v-6a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v6a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2zm0 0V9a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2v10m-6 0a2 2 0 002 2h2a2 2 0 002-2m0 0V5a2 2 0 012-2h2a2 2 0 012 2v14a2 2 0 01-2 2h-2a2 2 0 01-2-2z"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight mb-6">
        <span class="text-transparent bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-600 to-pink-600">BC PNP vs CRS:</span> Which One?
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
        Two pathways to Canadian PR. One might be significantly easier for you. Here's how to decide.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <div class="space-y-16">
      
      <!-- Quick Answer -->
      <section>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-purple-50 to-pink-50 rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-10 border border-purple-100">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-4">The Quick Answer</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            <strong>BC PNP</strong> is the provincial system for British Columbia. <strong>CRS</strong> (Comprehensive Ranking System) is the federal Express Entry system for all of Canada. If you have a job offer in BC, especially in tech or healthcare, BC PNP often has <strong class="text-green-600">much lower score requirements</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Comparison Table -->
      <section>
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
        </div>
        
        <div class="bg-white rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
            <div class="bg-slate-900 px-6 py-4 text-white font-bold text-sm uppercase tracking-wider">Factor</div>
            <div class="bg-purple-600 px-6 py-4 text-white font-bold text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-center">BC PNP</div>
            <div class="bg-blue-600 px-6 py-4 text-white font-bold text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-center">Express Entry CRS</div>
          </div>
          <div class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">Max Score</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center text-slate-700">200 points</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center text-slate-700">1200 points</div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">Job Offer Required?</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center"><span class="bg-red-100 text-red-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold">Yes (Usually)</span></div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center"><span class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold">No</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">Typical Cut-off</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center font-bold text-green-600">85-115 points</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center font-bold text-red-600">480-520+ points</div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">Draw Frequency</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center text-slate-700">Weekly</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center text-slate-700">Bi-weekly</div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">Targeted Draws</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center"><span class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold">Yes (Tech, Health)</span></div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center"><span class="bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-sm font-bold">Yes (Category-based)</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-3">
              <div class="px-6 py-4 font-medium text-slate-900 bg-slate-50">PNP Nomination Bonus</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center text-slate-400">N/A</div>
              <div class="px-6 py-4 text-center font-bold text-purple-600">+600 points</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Who Benefits -->
      <section>
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">Who Benefits from BC PNP?</h2>
        </div>
        
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-[2rem] border-2 border-green-200 shadow-sm">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
              <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-green-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"></path>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h3 class="font-black text-green-800 text-lg">Great for BC PNP</h3>
            </div>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-green-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Already have a job offer in BC</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-green-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Work in Tech, Healthcare, or Trades</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-green-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Lower CRS score (under 470)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-green-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Strong wage ($50+/hr)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-green-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Want to live specifically in BC</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-[2rem] border-2 border-blue-200 shadow-sm">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
              <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-blue-100 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-blue-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"></path>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h3 class="font-black text-blue-800 text-lg">Better for Express Entry</h3>
            </div>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>No job offer yet</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>High CRS score (500+)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Canadian education (bonus points)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>Flexible on which province</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                <span class="text-blue-500 font-bold">✓</span>
                <span>French language skills</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- NEW: Cost & Timeline Analysis -->
      <section>
          <div class="text-center mb-10">
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">Cost & Timeline Analysis</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600">BC PNP is more expensive but often more predictable for workers in BC.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
             <div class="bg-slate-900 rounded-[2rem] p-8 text-white relative">
                 <div class="absolute top-4 right-4 bg-purple-600 text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase">BC PNP + Federal</div>
                 <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-6">Cost Breakdown</h3>
                 <div class="space-y-4">
                    <div class="flex justify-between border-b border-white/10 pb-2">
                       <span class="text-slate-300">Registration (SIRS)</span>
                       <span class="font-mono text-green-400">Free</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex justify-between border-b border-white/10 pb-2">
                       <span class="text-slate-300">BC PNP Application Fee</span>
                       <span class="font-mono text-white">$1,475</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex justify-between border-b border-white/10 pb-2">
                       <span class="text-slate-300">Federal PR Processing</span>
                       <span class="font-mono text-white">$950</span>
                    </div>
                     <div class="flex justify-between border-b border-white/10 pb-2">
                       <span class="text-slate-300">Right of PR Fee</span>
                       <span class="font-mono text-white">$575</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex justify-between pt-2">
                       <span class="font-bold">Total Estimate</span>
                       <span class="font-bold text-2xl text-purple-400">~$3,000</span>
                    </div>
                 </div>
                 <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mt-4 italic">*Single applicant. Prices subject to change.</p>
             </div>

             <div class="bg-white rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-200 p-8">
                 <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-6 text-slate-900">Processing Timeline</h3>
                 <div class="relative space-y-8 pl-8 border-l-2 border-slate-100">
                    <div class="relative">
                       <div class="absolute -left-[39px] top-1 w-5 h-5 bg-purple-600 rounded-full border-4 border-white"></div>
                       <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">BC PNP Registration</h4>
                       <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">Instant score.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="relative">
                       <div class="absolute -left-[39px] top-1 w-5 h-5 bg-purple-600 rounded-full border-4 border-white"></div>
                       <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Invitation to Apply</h4>
                       <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">1-4 weeks (if score is high enough).</p>
                    </div>
                     <div class="relative">
                       <div class="absolute -left-[39px] top-1 w-5 h-5 bg-purple-600 rounded-full border-4 border-white"></div>
                       <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Provincial Processing</h4>
                       <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">2-3 months (Tech) to 3-4 months (Skills).</p>
                    </div>
                     <div class="relative">
                       <div class="absolute -left-[39px] top-1 w-5 h-5 bg-blue-600 rounded-full border-4 border-white"></div>
                       <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Federal PR Application</h4>
                       <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">Non-Express Entry: 12-16 months.<br>Express Entry linked: 4-6 months.</p>
                    </div>
                 </div>
             </div>
          </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Hybrid Strategy -->
      <section>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-slate-900 to-slate-800 rounded-[2rem] p-8 sm:p-10 text-white">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-amber-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-white" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.663 17h4.673M12 3v1m6.364 1.636l-.707.707M21 12h-1M4 12H3m3.343-5.657l-.707-.707m2.828 9.9a5 5 0 117.072 0l-.548.547A3.374 3.374 0 0014 18.469V19a2 2 0 11-4 0v-.531c0-.895-.356-1.754-.988-2.386l-.548-.547z"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <span class="text-amber-400 font-bold uppercase text-sm tracking-wider">Pro Strategy</span>
          </div>
          
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4">The Hybrid Approach (EEBC)</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            This is the "Gold Standard" for immigration strategy. It combines the ease of BC PNP with the speed of Express Entry.
          </p>
          
          <div class="space-y-4">
             <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-amber-400">
               <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-400 mb-2">Step 1: Enter Express Entry Pool</h4>
               <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Create a federal profile. Even if your score is 350 (too low), just get into the pool to get your "Express Entry Profile Number" and "Job Seeker Validation Code".</p>
             </div>
             
             <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-amber-400">
               <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-400 mb-2">Step 2: Apply to BC PNP "Express Entry BC"</h4>
               <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">When registering with SIRS, select the "Express Entry BC" option. You will need your federal profile numbers.</p>
             </div>
             
              <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-xl p-6 border-l-4 border-amber-400">
               <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-400 mb-2">Step 3: Get Nominated & Claim +600 Points</h4>
               <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Once BC nominates you, they notify the federal system. Your CRS score jumps by 600 points (e.g., 350 -> 950). You are now guaranteed an ITA in the next federal draw.</p>
             </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- When NOT to use BC PNP -->
      <section>
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-3">When NOT to Use BC PNP</h2>
        </div>
        
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] border border-red-100 flex gap-4">
            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-red-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-1">No Valid BC Job Offer</h3>
              <p class="text-red-800 text-sm">Without a full-time, indeterminate job offer from a BC employer, you cannot apply to most BC PNP streams.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] border border-red-100 flex gap-4">
            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-red-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-1">Committed to Another Province</h3>
              <p class="text-red-800 text-sm">Each province has its own PNP. If you want to live in Ontario, Alberta, etc., use their program instead.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="bg-red-50 p-6 rounded-[1.5rem] border border-red-100 flex gap-4">
            <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-red-100 rounded-full flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center">
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-red-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-1">Very High CRS Score Already</h3>
              <p class="text-red-800 text-sm">If you have a CRS of 500+, you might get an ITA directly through Express Entry without needing the PNP pathway.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <section>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-red-600 to-red-700 rounded-[2rem] p-10 sm:p-12 text-center text-white">
          <h3 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black mb-4">Calculate Your BC PNP Score</h3>
          <p class="text-red-100 mb-8 max-w-md mx-auto">Find out if BC PNP is your better pathway.</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center bg-white text-red-600 px-8 py-4 rounded-[1.5rem] font-black text-lg hover:bg-red-50 transition-colors shadow-xl">
            Open Calculator
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 ml-2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 7l5 5m0 0l-5 5m5-5H6"></path>
            </svg>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Detailed Scoring Breakdown -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">How Each System Scores You</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-[2rem] p-8 border border-slate-100 shadow-sm space-y-6">
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">The SIRS (Skills Immigration Registration System) used by BC PNP and the federal Comprehensive Ranking System (CRS) look superficially similar, but they reward different things. Understanding the differences helps you decide which pathway actually fits your profile - and where to spend your improvement effort.</p>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">SIRS rewards local commitment</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">SIRS allocates up to 60 of its 200 points to your BC job offer - hourly wage, TEER level of the role, and location. A $42/hr software developer role in Vancouver earns substantially more SIRS points than the same role at $32/hr. SIRS also rewards BC work experience (up to 20 points) and regional residency outside Metro Vancouver and the Capital Regional District. There are no points for adaptability, sibling-in-Canada, or French - all features that matter heavily in the federal CRS.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">CRS rewards human capital</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">CRS is built around what IRCC calls "core human capital" - age (max 110), education (max 150), language (max 160 first official + 30 second official), and Canadian work experience (max 80). Skill transferability combinations add up to 100 more points. Together these can produce a CRS of 470-500 before any job offer or PNP bonus. The +600-point provincial nomination boost is the largest single CRS factor and effectively guarantees an ITA at the next federal draw.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Which to optimize</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">If your age is over 35 or your education is below a master's, your CRS likely tops out around 450 - below recent cut-offs. SIRS, by contrast, can easily reach 100+ with a strong BC job offer and CLB 8 language, well above typical BC PNP cut-offs. For applicants already in BC on a work permit, SIRS is almost always the easier system. For applicants under 30 with a master's degree and CLB 9+, the federal CRS pool may produce an ITA without ever needing a job offer.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Real Profiles -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">Four Real Applicant Profiles</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Profile 1: Aisha, 33, Software Engineer in Vancouver</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">CLB 9 English, no French, master's degree from India, three years of Canadian work experience, $108,000 base salary at a Vancouver-based fintech. CRS: 462 (below the typical 480 cut-off for general draws). SIRS: 138 (well above the Tech draw cut-off of around 90). <strong>Best path: BC PNP Tech via Express Entry BC.</strong> Total estimated timeline: 8-9 months from SIRS to PR.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Profile 2: Mateus, 28, PhD Researcher, No Job Offer</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">CLB 10 English, CLB 8 French (TEF Canada), PhD from a Canadian university, two years of Canadian post-doc experience. CRS: 521. SIRS: ineligible without a BC job offer. <strong>Best path: federal Express Entry, French-aligned category draw.</strong> Expected ITA within 4-12 weeks of entering the pool.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Profile 3: Priya, 41, Registered Nurse, Interior Health Job Offer</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">CLB 8 English, BSN from the Philippines, 12 years nursing experience, full-time job offer from Interior Health at $48/hr. CRS: 388 (too low for the federal pool). SIRS: 142, but eligible for direct Health Authority invitation regardless of SIRS score. <strong>Best path: BC PNP Health Authority stream.</strong> Total expected timeline: 6-8 months.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Profile 4: Daniel, 36, Construction Project Manager in Calgary</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">CLB 7 English, bachelor's degree, six years Canadian work experience in Alberta. No BC job offer. CRS: 451. <strong>BC PNP is not an option without a BC job.</strong> Best path: Alberta AAIP, Ontario OINP Employer Job Offer, or federal Express Entry trades category. Lesson: PNPs are tied to province of residence and the BC PNP only helps people committed to BC.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Strategic Tips -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">Strategic Tips & Common Mistakes</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
          <ul class="space-y-4 text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <li><strong>Always create an Express Entry profile, even if your CRS is low.</strong> The profile number and Job Seeker Validation Code are required to apply for Express Entry BC. Creating one is free and the profile stays active for 12 months.</li>
            <li><strong>Do not assume "BC PNP is easier" applies to every stream.</strong> The Entry Level and Semi-Skilled stream is dramatically harder to use in 2026 because of allocation cuts. Skilled Worker, Tech, and Health Authority remain the practical streams for most applicants.</li>
            <li><strong>Match your NOC code carefully.</strong> A job titled "Project Manager" can fall under NOC 10019, 20012, 21222, or 70010 depending on industry. The wrong NOC can disqualify you from both BC PNP and Express Entry.</li>
            <li><strong>If your CRS is between 470 and 490 and you have a BC offer, do both.</strong> Stay in the Express Entry pool while applying to BC PNP. If you get nominated, the +600 boost guarantees an ITA. If your CRS rises (new language test, more experience), you may get an ITA federally first.</li>
            <li><strong>Watch the BC PNP draw history.</strong> The province publishes invitation cut-offs after each draw. Patterns over six months reveal which streams are easy entry vs. saturated.</li>
            <li><strong>Do not pay agents promising "guaranteed nomination."</strong> Neither BC PNP nor IRCC works with paid intermediaries beyond licensed RCICs and lawyers. Most score-boosting promises are scams.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Can I apply to both BC PNP and Express Entry at the same time?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes - and you should. Maintain an active federal Express Entry profile while pursuing a BC PNP nomination. They are complementary, not competing, systems. The Express Entry BC sub-stream actually requires both at once.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>What if I get an ITA from Express Entry before my BC PNP decision?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">You can accept the federal ITA and proceed with the standard Express Entry PR application. You no longer need BC PNP at that point. Withdraw your BC PNP registration to free up an invitation slot for another applicant.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Does the BC PNP +600 CRS bonus expire?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. Your provincial nomination certificate is valid for 6 months from the date of issue. You must receive your federal ITA and submit your e-APR within that window or risk losing the +600 boost. Most applicants are invited at the very next federal PNP-specific draw.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Is the BC PNP Tech stream still accepting Software Developers in 2026?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Yes. NOC 21232 (Software Developers and Programmers) remains one of the top three invited occupations in BC PNP Tech draws, alongside NOC 21311 (Computer Engineers) and NOC 21231 (Software Engineers and Designers).</div>
          </details>
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Do I need an LMIA for BC PNP?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">No. BC PNP does not require a Labour Market Impact Assessment (LMIA). The employer must register with BC PNP and demonstrate they offered the position to Canadian citizens and permanent residents first, but the LMIA process itself is not part of the application.</div>
          </details>
          <details class="group bg-white rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 open:border-purple-200 open:shadow-md transition-all">
            <summary class="flex justify-between items-center font-bold text-slate-900 p-6 cursor-pointer list-none"><span>Can a high CRS score replace a BC job offer for BC PNP?</span><span class="text-purple-600">▼</span></summary>
            <div class="px-6 pb-6 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">No. With limited exceptions (post-graduate International stream, doctors via Health Authority), BC PNP requires a full-time, indeterminate job offer from an eligible BC employer. CRS score does not substitute for this requirement.</div>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Decision Framework -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">A Step-by-Step Decision Framework</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 border border-slate-100 shadow-sm space-y-5">
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Use this five-step framework to pick between BC PNP and federal Express Entry before you spend money on language tests, credential assessments, or consultant fees. Each step takes only a few minutes and clarifies whether one or both pathways realistically lead to PR for your profile in 2026.</p>
          <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <li><strong>Estimate your CRS.</strong> Use IRCC's free CRS tool. If you are at or above 510, federal Express Entry is your fastest pathway and you may not need a PNP at all. If you are between 460 and 510, you are in the "borderline" zone where a PNP nomination dramatically improves your odds. Below 460, a PNP nomination is effectively essential.</li>
            <li><strong>Check your tie to British Columbia.</strong> Do you live in BC now, hold a BC work permit, or have a written job offer from a BC employer? If yes, BC PNP is viable. If no, focus on the province where you actually have ties (Alberta AAIP, Ontario OINP, etc.) or rely on federal Express Entry.</li>
            <li><strong>Map your NOC code to BC PNP streams.</strong> Tech, Health Authority, Skilled Worker, and International Graduate streams each accept specific occupations. Confirm your job duties match the NOC code your employer will use on its BC PNP employer registration.</li>
            <li><strong>Estimate your SIRS score.</strong> Use the <a href="/bc-pnp-calculator" class="text-purple-600 underline">BC PNP calculator</a>. A SIRS above 100 with a priority occupation typically wins an invitation within a few weeks. Scores in the 80s require patience or score improvement.</li>
            <li><strong>Build a parallel timeline.</strong> Even if BC PNP is your primary path, keep a federal Express Entry profile active. Many applicants get nominated provincially while their CRS rises (new language test, more Canadian experience) and the +600 boost finalizes their ITA.</li>
          </ol>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">A common, costly mistake is investing months in only one system and discovering too late that the other was a better fit. Treat both as parallel processes from day one and let the data decide which delivers your ITA first.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Documents Side-by-Side -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 mb-6">Document Requirements Side-by-Side</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Both systems demand the same core documents - language test, ECA, passport, work history letters, police certificates, and medical exam - but BC PNP adds employer-side documents that take time to produce. Knowing the difference helps you plan the gathering phase.</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li><strong>BC PNP additionally requires:</strong> employer registration on BCPNPOnline, job offer letter signed by both parties, business license, T4 summary or proof of revenue, recruitment efforts documentation, BC PNP application fee ($1,475 CAD), and a settlement plan demonstrating intent to live in BC.</li>
            <li><strong>Federal Express Entry additionally requires:</strong> NOC duties mapped exactly to your reference letters, proof of funds at the LICO threshold (currently $14,690 CAD for a single applicant in 2026), and a recent Letter of Acceptance for any post-secondary credential.</li>
            <li><strong>Shared documents:</strong> IELTS General, CELPIP General, TEF Canada, or TCF Canada language test results valid within 2 years; WES, ICAS, IQAS, CES, or ICES Educational Credential Assessment valid within 5 years; passport copy; current and previous work reference letters with job duties, hours per week, and salary.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">Many applicants assume they can reuse a single set of documents across both systems. In practice, BC PNP wants very specific employer-side paperwork that IRCC does not, and IRCC wants proof of funds that BC PNP does not. Build a master document tracker before starting either application.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

